00:01:30.040 --> 00:01:34.200
&gt;&gt; These are the core beliefs of
the Indian Law Resource Center.

00:01:34.200 --> 00:01:38.330
For more than 30 years, the
Center has been a global force,

00:01:38.330 --> 00:01:41.700
challenging and building legal
frameworks, to enhance the lives

00:01:41.700 --> 00:01:43.300
of indigenous peoples.

00:01:43.300 --> 00:01:46.690
One of the major causes of
the economic and social ills

00:01:46.690 --> 00:01:49.980
within native communities
is the unfair legal rules

00:01:49.980 --> 00:01:53.030
that apply only to native
peoples in the United States.

00:01:53.030 --> 00:01:56.430
We have taken on cases on
behalf of the Timbisha Shoshone,

00:01:56.430 --> 00:01:58.930
and the Mohawk Nations,
and others with the goal

00:01:58.930 --> 00:02:01.560
of changing some of these laws.

00:02:01.560 --> 00:02:03.840
We also seek to strengthen
sovereignty rights

00:02:03.840 --> 00:02:06.760
so that tribes can better
protect their people.

00:02:06.760 --> 00:02:08.730
This is more critical
now than ever.

00:02:08.730 --> 00:02:13.800
&gt;&gt; One in three native women
will be raped in her lifetime

00:02:13.800 --> 00:02:16.790
and three out of five will
be physically assaulted.

00:02:16.790 --> 00:02:18.970
The center's hallmark
work is related

00:02:18.970 --> 00:02:21.420
to the United Nation's
Declaration on the Rights

00:02:21.420 --> 00:02:23.390
of Indigenous Peoples.

00:02:23.390 --> 00:02:25.610
&gt;&gt; Robert T. Coulter: We wanted
to be sure, and we wanted

00:02:25.610 --> 00:02:30.600
to establish legal rules
that would make it clear

00:02:30.600 --> 00:02:35.220
that indigenous peoples
really do own their land.

00:02:35.220 --> 00:02:37.460
They really do have full

00:02:37.460 --> 00:02:40.920
and complete legal
rights to those lands.

00:02:40.920 --> 00:02:44.730
But they have rights that can
be protected in the courts.

00:02:44.730 --> 00:02:48.550
Rights that are protected
by definite rules of law

00:02:48.550 --> 00:02:53.600
that can't just be thrown out or
ignored by courts or countries

00:02:53.600 --> 00:02:54.900
and their governments.

00:02:54.900 --> 00:02:56.250
&gt;&gt; The declaration was adopted

00:02:56.250 --> 00:02:59.290
by the UN General
Assembly in 2007.

00:02:59.290 --> 00:03:00.620
&gt;&gt; President Barack Obama:
And as you know, in April,

00:03:00.620 --> 00:03:02.830
we announced that we were
reviewing our position

00:03:02.830 --> 00:03:06.260
on the UN Declaration on the
Rights of Indigenous Peoples.

00:03:06.260 --> 00:03:07.560
And today, I can announce

00:03:07.560 --> 00:03:09.310
that the United States
is lending its support

00:03:09.310 --> 00:03:12.320
to this declaration.

00:03:12.320 --> 00:03:14.700
&gt;&gt; This is just a
snapshot of the work coming

00:03:14.700 --> 00:03:19.070
out of both the Helena, Montana
and Washington DC offices.

00:03:19.070 --> 00:03:21.640
We at the Indian Law
Resource Center are experts

00:03:21.640 --> 00:03:24.010
in Indian law, working
to protect

00:03:24.010 --> 00:03:26.970
and preserve indigenous
peoples and their communities.

00:03:26.970 --> 00:03:30.000
Our ultimate goal is to
make positive contributions

00:03:30.000 --> 00:03:32.910
that will have lasting effects.

00:03:32.910 --> 00:03:36.970
Visit www.indianlaw.org.

00:03:41.010 --> 00:03:42.310
&gt;&gt; Carla Davis-Castro:

00:03:42.310 --> 00:03:45.630
Our speakers today are Armstrong
A. Wiggins, the director

00:03:45.630 --> 00:03:48.900
of the Indian Law Resource
Center, Washington DC office.

00:03:48.900 --> 00:03:51.920
Born in Nicaragua, Mr.
Wiggins is a Moskito Indian

00:03:51.920 --> 00:03:54.280
from the village of
Karata in Nicaragua.

00:03:54.280 --> 00:03:58.130
He was the founder of the Indian
organization called [foreign

00:03:58.130 --> 00:04:01.370
language], and was the
coordinator of municipal affairs

00:04:01.370 --> 00:04:04.310
of the east coast for the
government of Nicaragua.

00:04:04.310 --> 00:04:06.230
He was also the national
representative

00:04:06.230 --> 00:04:08.880
of the regional Indian
organization [foreign language].

00:04:08.880 --> 00:04:14.130
Mr. Wiggins was arrested
twice during both the Somoza

00:04:14.130 --> 00:04:17.190
and the Sandinista regimes and
became a political prisoner

00:04:17.190 --> 00:04:19.740
because of his work to
promote human rights

00:04:19.740 --> 00:04:21.160
for his people in Nicaragua.

00:04:21.160 --> 00:04:25.870
In 1981, Mr. Wiggins
was forced into exile.

00:04:25.870 --> 00:04:28.920
It was at this time that he
began working for the Center

00:04:28.920 --> 00:04:31.810
as the director of its Central
and South America program.

00:04:31.810 --> 00:04:33.940
For the past 20 years,
he has worked

00:04:33.940 --> 00:04:37.400
on numerous human rights cases
involving indigenous peoples,

00:04:37.400 --> 00:04:39.960
including the Yano
Nami in Brazil,

00:04:39.960 --> 00:04:42.890
the case against Nicaragua in
the inter-American commission

00:04:42.890 --> 00:04:46.300
on human rights in 1984,
which led to changes

00:04:46.300 --> 00:04:49.230
in the constitution of
Nicaragua for the recognition

00:04:49.230 --> 00:04:51.150
of indigenous rights
and the creation

00:04:51.150 --> 00:04:55.120
of autonomous indigenous
regions in Nicaragua.

00:04:55.120 --> 00:04:58.480
He worked on the case
for the Maya in Belize.

00:04:58.480 --> 00:05:00.070
Mr. Wiggins played
a leading role

00:05:00.070 --> 00:05:01.590
in the precedent setting
[foreign language]

00:05:01.590 --> 00:05:04.040
in the Inter-American System.

00:05:04.040 --> 00:05:06.230
And he has also played
a critical role

00:05:06.230 --> 00:05:09.820
in the Center's standard setting
work with the United Nations

00:05:09.820 --> 00:05:12.770
and the organization
of American States,

00:05:12.770 --> 00:05:15.760
particularly regarding the
Declarations on the Rights

00:05:15.760 --> 00:05:17.190
of Indigenous Peoples.

00:05:17.190 --> 00:05:19.820
He currently supervises the
works of the Center dealing

00:05:19.820 --> 00:05:22.330
with human rights,
standards setting,

00:05:22.330 --> 00:05:24.930
and multi-lateral
development banks.

00:05:24.930 --> 00:05:28.930
Leonardo Crippa is an
international law scholar

00:05:28.930 --> 00:05:30.230
and practitioner.

00:05:30.230 --> 00:05:35.150
He holds a JD from the
National University of Tucuman

00:05:35.150 --> 00:05:40.050
in Argentina, and an LLM
from American University.

00:05:40.050 --> 00:05:42.030
As the Center for Justice

00:05:42.030 --> 00:05:43.980
and International
Law's staff attorney,

00:05:43.980 --> 00:05:46.690
he litigated several
human rights cases

00:05:46.690 --> 00:05:49.620
within the Inter-American
Human Right's System.

00:05:49.620 --> 00:05:51.810
In his current work
as the senior attorney

00:05:51.810 --> 00:05:53.760
of the Indian Law
Resource Center,

00:05:53.760 --> 00:05:57.700
he analyzes multi-lateral
development bank's policies,

00:05:57.700 --> 00:06:01.720
and continues to
practice international law

00:06:01.720 --> 00:06:03.390
within the United Nations

00:06:03.390 --> 00:06:06.140
and the Inter-American
Human Rights System.

00:06:06.140 --> 00:06:09.260
He is also the author of
papers on constitutional law,

00:06:09.260 --> 00:06:10.560
international law,

00:06:10.560 --> 00:06:13.350
and multi-lateral
development bank's policies.

