00:06:59.230 --> 00:07:01.950
So can you tell us, generally,
about the work that you do

00:07:01.950 --> 00:07:05.520
at the Indian Law Resource
Center, and a little bit more

00:07:05.520 --> 00:07:08.950
about the structure and how
the organization came to be?

00:07:10.060 --> 00:07:13.000
&gt;&gt; Armstrong Wiggins: The Indian
Resource Center is founded

00:07:13.000 --> 00:07:15.400
by Robert T. Coulter.

00:07:15.400 --> 00:07:20.290
He's a Potowatomi person.

00:07:20.290 --> 00:07:24.210
He's also a judge
in this community.

00:07:24.210 --> 00:07:29.670
He represents his nation to the
organization of American States

00:07:29.670 --> 00:07:31.360
and the United Nations.

00:07:31.360 --> 00:07:37.470
Tim went to Columbia Law
School and, from law school,

00:07:37.470 --> 00:07:41.010
he realized that one of
the biggest challenges

00:07:41.010 --> 00:07:46.750
that indigenous peoples faced
was the very lack of law

00:07:46.750 --> 00:07:50.100
that indigenous people
understand.

00:07:50.100 --> 00:07:52.010
And the law was very
discriminatory

00:07:52.010 --> 00:07:54.210
against indigenous people.

00:07:54.210 --> 00:08:00.170
We're talking about the
European legal system that came

00:08:00.170 --> 00:08:03.150
to the Americas that
indigenous people had a hard

00:08:03.150 --> 00:08:04.450
time understanding.

00:08:04.450 --> 00:08:09.730
&gt;&gt; Could you speak up?

00:08:09.730 --> 00:08:11.130
&gt;&gt; Armstrong Wiggins: We're
talking about the laws

00:08:11.130 --> 00:08:13.060
that came from Europe.

00:08:13.060 --> 00:08:16.940
Indigenous peoples had
a hard time fighting

00:08:16.940 --> 00:08:19.050
against that system.

00:08:19.050 --> 00:08:23.790
In the past, they can
understand their struggle

00:08:23.790 --> 00:08:25.480
between the cowboys and Indians.

00:08:25.480 --> 00:08:27.970
And you know that
most of the time

00:08:27.970 --> 00:08:31.650
that cowboys were the good
guys, Indians was the bad guys.

00:08:31.650 --> 00:08:35.770
And so that was a
very heavy challenge.

00:08:35.770 --> 00:08:39.630
And when the legal
system come, and very,

00:08:39.630 --> 00:08:44.100
very racist legal system
against the Indian government

00:08:44.100 --> 00:08:48.120
that existed in this
continent, it was very hard.

00:08:48.120 --> 00:08:50.560
First, because they don't
understand the language,

00:08:50.560 --> 00:08:52.180
they don't speak English.

00:08:52.180 --> 00:08:55.560
And so it was very
discriminatory.

00:08:55.560 --> 00:08:59.110
So after Tim went to
law school and came out,

00:08:59.110 --> 00:09:03.400
he decided that he needs to form
the Indian Law Resource Center

00:09:03.400 --> 00:09:07.640
to represent traditional
Indian governments

00:09:07.640 --> 00:09:14.610
against the Washington influence
of how to destroy Indian way

00:09:14.610 --> 00:09:19.030
of thinking, Indian philosophy,
Indian way of looking issues.

00:09:19.030 --> 00:09:22.430
And so they gave lots of money
to Bureau of Indian Affairs

00:09:22.430 --> 00:09:25.800
to destroy traditional
Indian governments.

00:09:25.800 --> 00:09:27.130
And you know what happened.

00:09:27.130 --> 00:09:30.750
History will tell you what
happened to indigenous people

00:09:30.750 --> 00:09:33.730
from this terrible
legal thinking.

00:09:33.730 --> 00:09:38.490
And so Tim wanted to create
Indian Law Resource Center

00:09:38.490 --> 00:09:41.140
so that we can represent
them for free.

00:09:41.140 --> 00:09:44.820
Because lawyers were one
of our Indian worst enemy.

00:09:44.820 --> 00:09:47.540
Because they were
represent them, and then,

00:09:47.540 --> 00:09:51.530
if they do win a case,
they owe the lawyer more

00:09:51.530 --> 00:09:53.860
than what they were
supposed to pay.

00:09:53.860 --> 00:09:55.990
And so they didn't get
any benefit from it.

00:09:55.990 --> 00:10:00.710
So the Indian Law Resource
Center is a non-profit office

00:10:00.710 --> 00:10:04.130
that we don't charge
our clients.

00:10:04.130 --> 00:10:10.820
We find our own money to
represent native people.

00:10:10.820 --> 00:10:12.120
The other interesting thing is

00:10:12.120 --> 00:10:17.190
that we do not accept
government money.

00:10:17.190 --> 00:10:21.090
We raise our private
money from foundations,

00:10:21.090 --> 00:10:25.860
individuals to represent
Indian governments.

00:10:25.860 --> 00:10:27.860
We do not individual,

00:10:27.860 --> 00:10:31.190
we represent collective
governments.

00:10:31.190 --> 00:10:34.760
So that's how Indian Law
Resource Center was created

00:10:34.760 --> 00:10:37.690
and founded in 1978.

00:10:37.690 --> 00:10:41.120
Since then, we've been there.

00:10:41.120 --> 00:10:45.770
We settle in Washington DC
at the Eastern Market area,

00:10:45.770 --> 00:10:48.220
because we're close to
the Library of Congress.

00:10:48.220 --> 00:10:50.590
In the old days, we
used to come here a lot.

00:10:50.590 --> 00:10:54.250
We used to get to know
everybody at the legal stop.

00:10:54.250 --> 00:10:57.510
Now, don't you don't see me
anymore because of internet.

00:10:57.510 --> 00:11:02.500
[ Laughing ]

00:11:02.500 --> 00:11:04.270
But now we don't come.

00:11:04.270 --> 00:11:05.570
&gt;&gt; Carrie N. Lyons: Right.

00:11:05.570 --> 00:11:07.630
&gt;&gt; Armstrong Wiggins: So that's
the Indian Law Resource Center.

00:11:07.630 --> 00:11:10.280
So then Tim decided
to move to Helena,

00:11:10.280 --> 00:11:12.990
Montana because there are
more indigenous peoples there

00:11:12.990 --> 00:11:14.790
so then work with them closer.

00:11:14.790 --> 00:11:16.090
&gt;&gt; Carrie N. Lyons: Right.

00:11:16.090 --> 00:11:17.390
&gt;&gt; Armstrong Wiggins:
And so the office is--

00:11:17.390 --> 00:11:22.110
the Washington DC office
deals with the Hill here,

00:11:22.110 --> 00:11:26.180
the Congress, the White House,
the OAS, the Organization

00:11:26.180 --> 00:11:28.740
of American States because
you have the Inter-American

00:11:28.740 --> 00:11:31.720
Commission on Human Rights,
the Inter-American Court,

00:11:31.720 --> 00:11:35.810
and the World Bank, and the
Inter-American Development Bank.

00:11:35.810 --> 00:11:40.010
All this has to with policy
affecting indigenous people.

00:11:40.010 --> 00:11:44.700
Because the bad economic policy
also affect indigenous people,

00:11:44.700 --> 00:11:47.560
to take away their land
and their resources.

00:11:47.560 --> 00:11:49.450
And a lot of people
still believe

00:11:49.450 --> 00:11:51.120
that we're against development.

00:11:51.120 --> 00:11:53.150
We are not against development.

00:11:53.150 --> 00:11:55.950
We are against the
kind of development

00:11:55.950 --> 00:11:58.570
that the capitalist system bring

00:11:58.570 --> 00:12:00.930
to the inter-indigenous
community

00:12:00.930 --> 00:12:02.370
that take away their land.

00:12:02.370 --> 00:12:06.990
So we believe in sustainable
economic development.

00:12:06.990 --> 00:12:08.540
&gt;&gt; Carrie N. Lyons:
Right, right.

00:12:08.540 --> 00:12:10.160
Leo, do you have
anything to add?

00:12:10.160 --> 00:12:11.460
&gt;&gt; Leonardo A. Crippa: Yes.

00:12:11.460 --> 00:12:12.760
I have something to add.

00:12:12.760 --> 00:12:14.140
Despite the fact

00:12:14.140 --> 00:12:19.420
that [inaudible] I found
the Center is unique

00:12:19.420 --> 00:12:23.010
in the way it presents
tribes, communities,

00:12:23.010 --> 00:12:27.360
because the way the
Center handles the cases,

00:12:27.360 --> 00:12:30.590
it's a very long process,

00:12:30.590 --> 00:12:34.610
through which the Center
attorneys will, basically,

00:12:34.610 --> 00:12:36.850
sit down with the communities

00:12:36.850 --> 00:12:39.370
who they are attempting
to represent.

00:12:39.370 --> 00:12:41.830
They will assess their-- yes.

00:12:41.830 --> 00:12:44.030
The attorneys will
assess their legal means,

00:12:44.030 --> 00:12:47.950
the aspirations of
their communities.

00:12:47.950 --> 00:12:49.250
&gt;&gt; Carrie N. Lyons:
Oh, thank you.

00:12:49.250 --> 00:12:54.290
&gt;&gt; Leonardo A. Crippa: The
legal systems of the country,

00:12:54.290 --> 00:12:57.690
with the local council that
the community will select

00:12:57.690 --> 00:12:59.420
in the country.

00:12:59.420 --> 00:13:01.840
We will build a legal strategy.

00:13:01.840 --> 00:13:04.290
And that works.

00:13:04.290 --> 00:13:10.280
We, basically, translate
into political strategy,

00:13:10.280 --> 00:13:13.490
the political aspiration
of the community based

00:13:13.490 --> 00:13:16.930
on international laws,
especially human rights law.

00:13:16.930 --> 00:13:18.230
That's unique.

00:13:18.230 --> 00:13:20.690
I've done that over
here in the Center,

00:13:20.690 --> 00:13:23.530
and I work with [inaudible]
another organization

00:13:23.530 --> 00:13:27.230
that also handles
cases internationally.

00:13:27.230 --> 00:13:32.050
But the Center is unique
in that way of working

00:13:32.050 --> 00:13:35.100
with the communities
from the very beginning

00:13:35.100 --> 00:13:39.020
and building the legal
strategy from the bottom.

00:13:39.020 --> 00:13:40.320
&gt;&gt; Carrie N. Lyons: Well,
this leads-- oh yes.

00:13:40.320 --> 00:13:41.620
&gt;&gt; Armstrong Wiggins:
And I want to--

00:13:41.620 --> 00:13:43.480
I want to add to that
because that is very important

00:13:43.480 --> 00:13:49.370
to understand what we do is the
political leader's speeches is

00:13:49.370 --> 00:13:51.680
very important to us.

00:13:51.680 --> 00:13:53.990
When you are thinking
about environmental issue,

00:13:53.990 --> 00:13:56.680
when you thinking about land
rights issue, when you thinking

00:13:56.680 --> 00:14:00.390
about how we live collectively

00:14:00.390 --> 00:14:03.830
for generations,
in this continent.

00:14:03.830 --> 00:14:05.770
So we take that.

00:14:05.770 --> 00:14:09.260
We listen to them, and
we turn the project,

00:14:09.260 --> 00:14:13.630
their political speeches,
into a legal project

00:14:13.630 --> 00:14:18.190
to educate what collective
rights mean, what land surface

00:14:18.190 --> 00:14:21.830
or surface mean to them,

00:14:21.830 --> 00:14:25.190
as compared to Europeans,
what they mean.

00:14:25.190 --> 00:14:28.470
What individual rights verses
collective rights mean.

00:14:28.470 --> 00:14:32.320
You know that European doesn't
believe in collective rights.

00:14:32.320 --> 00:14:35.480
Everything is individual rights.

00:14:35.480 --> 00:14:37.340
We do not really believe that.

00:14:37.340 --> 00:14:41.640
We also believe that their
human rights is collective

00:14:41.640 --> 00:14:43.260
and individual rights.

00:14:43.260 --> 00:14:44.560
You live with community.

00:14:44.560 --> 00:14:46.160
You live with your village.

00:14:46.160 --> 00:14:48.670
And you protect your
village people,

00:14:48.670 --> 00:14:51.380
not just you, individual.

00:14:51.380 --> 00:14:54.670
And that's where
unfairness come.

00:14:54.670 --> 00:14:57.910
That's where, when
people become rich, rich,

00:14:57.910 --> 00:14:59.530
and then you have poor, poor.

00:14:59.530 --> 00:15:05.370
You don't have that collectivity
way of sharing your resources

00:15:05.370 --> 00:15:07.540
that you have, your
land resources,

00:15:07.540 --> 00:15:09.990
whether it's gold, whatever.

00:15:09.990 --> 00:15:13.510
So that is why our way

00:15:13.510 --> 00:15:19.370
of thinking educate the legal
system in the United States.

00:15:19.370 --> 00:15:21.330
And that's what we
call law reform.

00:15:21.330 --> 00:15:23.610
Law reform is very important.

00:15:23.610 --> 00:15:26.330
And that's how Indian Law
Resource Center challenge the

00:15:26.330 --> 00:15:28.370
legal system in the
United States,

00:15:28.370 --> 00:15:30.900
and challenge university
law schools.

00:15:30.900 --> 00:15:35.990
Because we believe lawyers
have very influential position

00:15:35.990 --> 00:15:38.120
in our society in this country.

00:15:38.120 --> 00:15:39.970
Lawyers become president.

00:15:39.970 --> 00:15:42.830
Lawyers become senators,
most of them.

00:15:42.830 --> 00:15:48.250
Lawyers become judges, from
Supreme Court right down.

00:15:48.250 --> 00:15:51.370
And if they don't
understand our way of thinking

00:15:51.370 --> 00:15:56.000
and the legal way of indigenous
people look at their issues,

00:15:56.000 --> 00:15:58.210
their political issues, then,

00:15:58.210 --> 00:16:02.260
that's where discrimination
comes, sometimes by ignorance,

00:16:02.260 --> 00:16:04.430
not understanding
the power issue.

00:16:04.430 --> 00:16:06.950
So that's why the legal project.

00:16:06.950 --> 00:16:09.010
And one thing is very important.

00:16:09.010 --> 00:16:12.350
We don't tell our
clients what to do.

00:16:12.350 --> 00:16:15.770
They tell us what to do.

00:16:15.770 --> 00:16:19.550
Because in the past, lawyers
will tell them how they should

00:16:19.550 --> 00:16:21.530
think, how they should
do things.

00:16:21.530 --> 00:16:24.710
We want them to tell us.

00:16:24.710 --> 00:16:26.010
They're our boss.

00:16:26.010 --> 00:16:29.370
So that's how we
create a legal policy

00:16:29.370 --> 00:16:34.580
to help indigenous
people basic human rights.

00:16:34.580 --> 00:16:37.510
&gt;&gt; Carrie N. Lyons: Speaking
of law reform and cases, Leo,

00:16:37.510 --> 00:16:40.090
can you tell us about some
of the most interesting,

00:16:40.090 --> 00:16:43.020
or maybe the most
challenging cases you've had?

00:16:43.020 --> 00:16:44.320
&gt;&gt; Leonardo A. Crippa: Sure.

00:16:44.320 --> 00:16:48.380
I'll tell about the most
challenging one first.

00:16:48.380 --> 00:16:50.250
That was the Rapa Nui Case.

00:16:50.250 --> 00:16:55.780
Rapa Nui's the native of,
basically, Easter Island.

00:16:55.780 --> 00:17:01.930
An island part of the Polynesian
Triangle on the Pacific Ocean.

00:17:01.930 --> 00:17:04.270
&gt;&gt; Could you speak up again?

00:17:04.270 --> 00:17:05.990
I couldn't hear what that was.

00:17:05.990 --> 00:17:07.290
&gt;&gt; Leonardo A. Crippa: Rapa Nui?

00:17:07.290 --> 00:17:09.710
It's an island in
the Pacific Ocean.

00:17:09.710 --> 00:17:12.840
And the native people there
are called Rapa Nui too.

00:17:12.840 --> 00:17:17.120
And so the case-- but we
actually didn't have a case,

00:17:17.120 --> 00:17:21.860
but we got the request from
the Rapa Nui parliament.

00:17:21.860 --> 00:17:26.030
The request, basically, helped
them secure their lands--

00:17:26.030 --> 00:17:28.050
regain control over their lands.

00:17:28.050 --> 00:17:32.210
Because, in the early '90's,
the Chilean government,

00:17:32.210 --> 00:17:35.530
they moved them from
their traditional lands

00:17:35.530 --> 00:17:40.460
to a concentration camp in
the island called Hanga Roa.

00:17:40.460 --> 00:17:44.310
And in 1966, for the very first
time, they were, basically,

00:17:44.310 --> 00:17:48.690
released and were able to
walk free in their own island.

00:17:48.690 --> 00:17:53.140
They became, for the very
first time, citizens of Chile.

00:17:53.140 --> 00:17:59.320
And so it was around 2009,
we received this request.

00:17:59.320 --> 00:18:02.430
We had never heard about them.

00:18:02.430 --> 00:18:06.170
I was on vacation in Argentina
and they decided to put me

00:18:06.170 --> 00:18:09.140
in a plane and send
to me to Chile

00:18:09.140 --> 00:18:11.800
because it was a short flight.

00:18:11.800 --> 00:18:13.460
&gt;&gt; Carrie N. Lyons: So your
vacation was cut short?

00:18:13.460 --> 00:18:14.760
&gt;&gt; Leonardo A. Crippa: Yeah.

00:18:14.760 --> 00:18:16.060
&gt;&gt; Carrie N. Lyons: OK.

00:18:16.060 --> 00:18:17.710
&gt;&gt; Leonardo A. Crippa:
That's why I remember.

00:18:17.710 --> 00:18:22.760
And so, basically, in landed
in this island in the middle

00:18:22.760 --> 00:18:26.290
of the Pacific Ocean, a very
small one, with the population

00:18:26.290 --> 00:18:31.620
of about 5,000 people, around
4,000 were natives, Rapa Nui.

00:18:31.620 --> 00:18:34.440
All of them speak the language.

00:18:34.440 --> 00:18:36.050
They're Polynesian.

00:18:36.050 --> 00:18:37.350
&gt;&gt; Carrie N. Lyons: Leo, can
you speak up a little bit

00:18:37.350 --> 00:18:39.440
for the people in the far back?

00:18:39.440 --> 00:18:42.580
&gt;&gt; Leonardo A. Crippa: And
they decided to go back

00:18:42.580 --> 00:18:44.680
to their official lands.

00:18:44.680 --> 00:18:48.040
In the past there were
18 traditional lands.

00:18:48.040 --> 00:18:51.510
And so they plans to go back.

00:18:51.510 --> 00:18:55.440
What they found, in some
cases, were public offices,

00:18:55.440 --> 00:18:58.050
in other cases, business.

00:18:58.050 --> 00:19:02.590
And their own clan in that
area started to [inaudible].

00:19:02.590 --> 00:19:04.710
And so they were in the middle

00:19:04.710 --> 00:19:07.310
of that action when
I landed there.

00:19:07.310 --> 00:19:11.640
And it was challenging because
I had to assess, as I said,

00:19:11.640 --> 00:19:13.600
what were their legal means?

00:19:13.600 --> 00:19:16.660
How did Indian Law Resource
Center from Washington

00:19:16.660 --> 00:19:20.430
or Helena, Montana
could assist them?

00:19:20.430 --> 00:19:26.850
And I found myself visiting each
of the areas having reoccupied

00:19:26.850 --> 00:19:31.360
by the Rapa Nui families
and clans.

00:19:31.360 --> 00:19:35.050
I knew that Chile was
going to react violently,

00:19:35.050 --> 00:19:38.450
because there's a history
of how Chile, they interacts

00:19:38.450 --> 00:19:43.110
with the Mapuche people
in the south of Chile.

00:19:43.110 --> 00:19:46.500
And so, basically, after
a week of being there,

00:19:46.500 --> 00:19:51.940
I flew back to Washington DC,
reported back to Armstrong

00:19:51.940 --> 00:19:57.910
and Tim what I was
able to learn,

00:19:57.910 --> 00:20:00.480
reported about three
actions that we could take.

00:20:00.480 --> 00:20:02.360
One was immediate.

00:20:02.360 --> 00:20:04.820
We had to secure
the extra measures

00:20:04.820 --> 00:20:07.170
from the Inter-American
Commission on Human Rights here

00:20:07.170 --> 00:20:12.550
in Washington DC so that
preventative actions could be

00:20:12.550 --> 00:20:15.500
ordered to Chile so the
government of Chile would not,

00:20:15.500 --> 00:20:21.240
basically, act violently
against the people of Rapa Nui.

00:20:21.240 --> 00:20:22.540
That was around October.

00:20:22.540 --> 00:20:25.990
The second action
was, basically,

00:20:25.990 --> 00:20:29.460
recover a very important Moai.

00:20:29.460 --> 00:20:33.820
Some of you may know--
have heard about the Moai.

00:20:33.820 --> 00:20:39.880
It plays a very important
role in the Rapa Nui culture,

00:20:39.880 --> 00:20:47.390
in Rapa Nui sense, a traditional
occupation of each of the clans.

00:20:47.390 --> 00:20:51.880
And you will find statues
like this all over the island.

00:20:51.880 --> 00:20:56.730
They are based on a rectangular
base that is called ahu.

00:20:56.730 --> 00:20:59.610
And that's where the
ancestors of each

00:20:59.610 --> 00:21:01.790
of the families are buried.

00:21:01.790 --> 00:21:05.080
I didn't believe that
until they started

00:21:05.080 --> 00:21:07.860
to show me what was below.

00:21:12.360 --> 00:21:15.600
And so the second action
was, basically, try to cover

00:21:15.600 --> 00:21:18.600
from the [inaudible] one
of the most important Moai

00:21:18.600 --> 00:21:22.070
that was removed
from the island.

00:21:22.070 --> 00:21:24.560
It was being shown there.

00:21:24.560 --> 00:21:27.980
And the third one, which
was the most complex one,

00:21:27.980 --> 00:21:33.450
is the determination because
it is an [inaudible] of Chile.

00:21:33.450 --> 00:21:35.850
And so the first
one was challenging.

00:21:35.850 --> 00:21:39.770
I had to represent
about 4,000 people.

00:21:39.770 --> 00:21:43.550
They never took a legal
action against Chile.

00:21:43.550 --> 00:21:48.370
They prepared for the
very first time from us.

00:21:48.370 --> 00:21:51.270
So I started to get
the power of attorneys

00:21:51.270 --> 00:21:53.310
from each of the clans.

00:21:53.310 --> 00:21:58.180
And I ended up filing a request
for precautionary measures

00:21:58.180 --> 00:21:59.480
with the Inter-American
Commission

00:21:59.480 --> 00:22:01.970
for Human Rights here in DC.

00:22:01.970 --> 00:22:06.310
After two months of legal
debates, with regard of Chile,

00:22:06.310 --> 00:22:10.690
the Commission decided to grant
those protective measures.

00:22:10.690 --> 00:22:12.470
By the time it was granted,

00:22:12.470 --> 00:22:15.450
the entire island was
already militarized.

00:22:15.450 --> 00:22:17.120
There were Special Forces.

00:22:17.120 --> 00:22:25.920
And, I'll never forget this,
on December the 3rd of 2009,

00:22:25.920 --> 00:22:30.620
there was a huge operation
against each of the families.

00:22:30.620 --> 00:22:34.040
And most of them were
removed violently.

00:22:34.040 --> 00:22:38.460
And there were shots, people
lost their eyes, and so forth.

00:22:38.460 --> 00:22:41.580
Unfortunately, the
precautionary measures were

00:22:41.580 --> 00:22:43.310
granted afterwards.

00:22:43.310 --> 00:22:45.900
So I wasn't able
to prevent that.

00:22:45.900 --> 00:22:51.610
And it was very violent
situation.

00:22:51.610 --> 00:22:56.050
But in the end, the armed
forces were moved back

00:22:56.050 --> 00:22:57.570
to continental Chile.

00:22:57.570 --> 00:23:00.190
The government was
forced to have a dialogue

00:23:00.190 --> 00:23:04.400
with the traditional Rapa Nui
authorities for the purpose

00:23:04.400 --> 00:23:07.480
of discussing the issues
of their main concern.

00:23:07.480 --> 00:23:10.170
That happened for
over four years.

00:23:10.170 --> 00:23:14.440
And so I stopped the violence
in the end, but I wasn't able

00:23:14.440 --> 00:23:18.140
to stop the most bad operation
that happened against them.

00:23:18.140 --> 00:23:20.630
And so that was very
challenging to me.

00:23:20.630 --> 00:23:25.900
The most interesting one
case that I have right now is

00:23:25.900 --> 00:23:28.500
against Guatemala to report
Inter-American Commission

00:23:28.500 --> 00:23:30.160
on Human Rights.

00:23:30.160 --> 00:23:34.670
It is represented a small
Maya Q'eqchi' community

00:23:34.670 --> 00:23:37.990
in the northern part
of [inaudible].

00:23:37.990 --> 00:23:41.950
And it's a case where
this community has been

00:23:41.950 --> 00:23:45.980
under a land-titling program
for more than four years

00:23:45.980 --> 00:23:50.870
without getting the final
title because of irregularities

00:23:50.870 --> 00:23:53.510
in the land surveys
and the land--

00:23:53.510 --> 00:23:54.840
&gt;&gt; Carrie N. Lyons: So they're
supposed to get the land,

00:23:54.840 --> 00:23:56.690
but they haven't
actually gotten it yet.

00:23:56.690 --> 00:23:57.990
OK.

00:23:57.990 --> 00:23:59.850
&gt;&gt; Leonardo A. Crippa: And,
in the meantime, the Ministry

00:23:59.850 --> 00:24:07.140
of Mining has issued permits
to a private mining company

00:24:07.140 --> 00:24:10.910
to explore and exploit
legal on the land belonging

00:24:10.910 --> 00:24:13.120
to this one community.

00:24:13.120 --> 00:24:18.180
And so our lawsuit against
the land titling agency.

00:24:18.180 --> 00:24:20.690
We never thought we were going
to win, but we won that case.

00:24:20.690 --> 00:24:21.990
&gt;&gt; Carrie N. Lyons: Oh, good.

00:24:21.990 --> 00:24:25.680
&gt;&gt; Leonardo A. Crippa: And after
two years with non-process,

00:24:25.680 --> 00:24:28.930
unfortunately, the government
[inaudible] is not enforcing

00:24:28.930 --> 00:24:33.160
this court decision and
so we were, basically,

00:24:33.160 --> 00:24:37.930
we had to sue the government

00:24:37.930 --> 00:24:40.490
for Maya before the
Inter-American Commission.

00:24:40.490 --> 00:24:42.810
And this is now an
international case.

00:24:42.810 --> 00:24:46.600
We are seeking the international
responsibility of Guatemala

00:24:46.600 --> 00:24:50.280
because of the violation
of these community's right

00:24:50.280 --> 00:24:53.760
of property over the
lands that they possess.

00:24:53.760 --> 00:24:56.630
And it is now in the
responsibility stage.

00:24:56.630 --> 00:24:58.340
We won that stage.

00:24:58.340 --> 00:25:02.040
The commission has released the
responsibility report saying

00:25:02.040 --> 00:25:04.920
that we fulfilled all the
requirements set for the

00:25:04.920 --> 00:25:07.120
in American Commission
and Human Rights in May,

00:25:07.120 --> 00:25:10.910
Human Rights Treaty,
ratified by Guatemala.

00:25:10.910 --> 00:25:13.250
And now we are discussing
the merits.

00:25:13.250 --> 00:25:14.590
And it's very interesting

00:25:14.590 --> 00:25:19.870
because it touches
the very structure

00:25:19.870 --> 00:25:26.010
on how lands are taken away
from indigenous communities,

00:25:26.010 --> 00:25:29.520
based on how prevalent
the land survey

00:25:29.520 --> 00:25:32.900
and [inaudible] system
works in Guatemala.

00:25:32.900 --> 00:25:35.190
&gt;&gt; Carrie N. Lyons: Oh, so it
seems like whenever you do take

00:25:35.190 --> 00:25:38.200
up cases, that it's a
long-term commitment.

00:25:38.200 --> 00:25:41.150
And, you know, some of these
cases can take quite a while

00:25:41.150 --> 00:25:44.090
before they are ever resolved.

00:25:44.090 --> 00:25:46.920
&gt;&gt; Armstrong Wiggins: Yeah, I
remember that Leo came in later,

00:25:46.920 --> 00:25:50.360
but Indian Law Resource
Center biggest challenge--

00:25:50.360 --> 00:25:51.930
I mean, first of all,

00:25:51.930 --> 00:25:57.250
I'm a trained electrical
engineer for my first career.

00:25:57.250 --> 00:26:03.040
I never dreamed to be
speaking to you on legal

00:26:03.040 --> 00:26:04.620
and human rights issues.

00:26:04.620 --> 00:26:10.170
Because we used to-- and my
specialty was in antennae.

00:26:10.170 --> 00:26:12.250
I was supposed to be
an astronaut, right?

00:26:12.250 --> 00:26:16.070
That was my interest, you know,
an electrical engineer, pilot,

00:26:16.070 --> 00:26:19.350
go to Cape Kennedy, and go up.

00:26:19.350 --> 00:26:22.310
But my people, the Moskito
people called me back

00:26:22.310 --> 00:26:23.610
to come home.

00:26:23.610 --> 00:26:25.830
And that's how I get
involved in politics

00:26:25.830 --> 00:26:28.490
and end up in jail twice.

00:26:28.490 --> 00:26:31.890
And I think one of the
things that very challenging

00:26:31.890 --> 00:26:35.710
from Indian Law Resource
Center perspective was

00:26:35.710 --> 00:26:38.150
to change things.

00:26:38.150 --> 00:26:42.430
And I guess that's what
happened between us,

00:26:42.430 --> 00:26:44.500
the Indian Law Resource Center.

00:26:44.500 --> 00:26:50.600
I think that one of the thing
that is very important is

00:26:50.600 --> 00:26:54.760
to work so close with
our leaders, our people.

00:26:54.760 --> 00:26:59.750
And work with them and do
the work that we need to do.

00:26:59.750 --> 00:27:05.500
And so our big, big, big first
challenges was in Nicaragua

00:27:05.500 --> 00:27:06.800
because of the cold war.

00:27:06.800 --> 00:27:08.940
And I'm sure all
of you know that.

00:27:08.940 --> 00:27:13.600
That divided us in Nicaragua,
divided Americans here

00:27:13.600 --> 00:27:17.020
because of Reagan administration
verses the Sandinista

00:27:17.020 --> 00:27:20.220
government, the contras, and
the human rights was divided.

00:27:20.220 --> 00:27:23.240
And I was in the
middle of it here,

00:27:23.240 --> 00:27:24.660
because I came out of jail here.

00:27:24.660 --> 00:27:27.780
And I challenged Senator
Kennedy, Senator McCain,

00:27:27.780 --> 00:27:30.760
Senator Dole, everybody
that there was not black

00:27:30.760 --> 00:27:32.640
and white in Central America.

00:27:32.640 --> 00:27:35.470
There was indigenous people
in the middle of that black

00:27:35.470 --> 00:27:38.110
and white, left and right.

00:27:38.110 --> 00:27:41.890
And so a lot of people
didn't take side.

00:27:41.890 --> 00:27:44.390
And I'm sure today,
in Washington,

00:27:44.390 --> 00:27:47.140
you will see what's going on.

00:27:47.140 --> 00:27:50.500
During the 80's, something
was going on like that too.

00:27:50.500 --> 00:27:53.810
They divide the family,
everybody was divided

00:27:53.810 --> 00:27:56.040
because of taking side.

00:27:56.040 --> 00:27:57.570
And Indian Law Resource
Center was

00:27:57.570 --> 00:27:59.620
in the middle of
that challenges.

00:27:59.620 --> 00:28:03.770
And from that challenges,
we have, now, in Nicaragua,

00:28:03.770 --> 00:28:06.410
autonomous government
with indigenous people.

00:28:06.410 --> 00:28:08.980
We have special system
that was set up.

00:28:08.980 --> 00:28:13.070
And our constitution
was improved.

00:28:13.070 --> 00:28:17.110
Because I bring cases
against Sandinista government

00:28:17.110 --> 00:28:20.650
that changed the Nicaraguan
constitution in 1987,

00:28:20.650 --> 00:28:24.100
and more progressive
towards indigenous people.

00:28:24.100 --> 00:28:29.740
We brought a legal case
against Yanomami case in Brazil.

00:28:29.740 --> 00:28:33.480
That now Yanomami have a
Yanomami park in Brazil.

00:28:33.480 --> 00:28:36.790
These were uncontacted
people that we represented.

00:28:36.790 --> 00:28:39.950
I went in there,
in their community.

00:28:39.950 --> 00:28:42.930
That you have to deal with
them to get their land rights.

00:28:42.930 --> 00:28:45.350
Now they have the
Yanomami Park in Brazil,

00:28:45.350 --> 00:28:50.630
one of the biggest land, kind
of, rights issue that happened

00:28:50.630 --> 00:28:54.870
in Brazil after the
Kayopi in Brazil.

00:28:54.870 --> 00:28:58.380
Then we bring the case against
Belize, the Mayan people.

00:28:58.380 --> 00:29:01.350
Now they have their
land rights approved

00:29:01.350 --> 00:29:03.920
by Belize Supreme Court,

00:29:03.920 --> 00:29:07.920
recognized by the regional
court in the Caribbean.

00:29:07.920 --> 00:29:09.220
It leads the Mayan people.

00:29:09.220 --> 00:29:10.970
Now they have their land rights.

00:29:10.970 --> 00:29:16.790
And then we have the biggest
one was Stanley vs. Nicaragua,

00:29:16.790 --> 00:29:22.090
which is now the international
community recognized indigenous

00:29:22.090 --> 00:29:25.850
people land throughout
the Inter-American system.

00:29:25.850 --> 00:29:29.040
And so those are some of the
challenges that we faced.

00:29:29.040 --> 00:29:32.230
And we struggled through that.

00:29:32.230 --> 00:29:37.810
And get support from the
international community.

00:29:37.810 --> 00:29:39.140
And the other challenge was

00:29:39.140 --> 00:29:41.260
to create international
development,

00:29:41.260 --> 00:29:45.620
international standard,
international declaration.

00:29:45.620 --> 00:29:48.350
Which, this is the
United Nation declaration.

00:29:48.350 --> 00:29:50.790
And this is the American
declaration on rights

00:29:50.790 --> 00:29:55.110
of indigenous people that
was just adopted last year,

00:29:55.110 --> 00:29:58.280
in the general assembly
of the [inaudible].

00:29:58.280 --> 00:30:00.800
So all this is here
if you people want

00:30:00.800 --> 00:30:03.070
to read what these declaration.

00:30:03.070 --> 00:30:04.910
&gt;&gt; Carrie N. Lyons: I think
they're out-- outside.

00:30:04.910 --> 00:30:06.210
&gt;&gt; Armstrong Wiggins: Outside.

00:30:06.210 --> 00:30:08.780
And so, this is what
Leo was talking

00:30:08.780 --> 00:30:11.200
about just not too long ago.

00:30:11.200 --> 00:30:15.210
So we face a lot of
challenges ahead of us still.

00:30:15.210 --> 00:30:18.530
And you see from even from
yesterday at the White House,

00:30:18.530 --> 00:30:20.590
we still faces a lot
of discrimination,

00:30:20.590 --> 00:30:23.080
a lot of struggle that we need

00:30:23.080 --> 00:30:26.240
to overcome regarding
our people rights.

00:30:26.240 --> 00:30:27.920
&gt;&gt; Carrie N. Lyons: Can
you tell us about some

