She just went back to
work for her government

00:32:51.200 --> 00:32:54.370
in Six Nations Territory.

00:32:54.370 --> 00:32:58.330
But these are wonderful
people fighting

00:32:58.330 --> 00:33:00.410
for this totally implement VAWA.

00:33:00.410 --> 00:33:02.380
&gt;&gt; Carrie N. Lyons:
Right, right, great.

00:33:02.380 --> 00:33:06.350
I know you also did some work
with the Seminoles in Florida

00:33:06.350 --> 00:33:09.390
and gave them the opportunity
to buy back some land.

00:33:09.390 --> 00:33:10.690
Could you tell us about that?

00:33:10.690 --> 00:33:13.070
&gt;&gt; Armstrong Wiggins: Yes,
Seminole, these are, you know,

00:33:13.070 --> 00:33:14.950
there's two group of Seminoles.

00:33:14.950 --> 00:33:18.830
One is the traditional
Seminoles, and the other one

00:33:18.830 --> 00:33:22.550
that is more successful
one, they have casinos.

00:33:22.550 --> 00:33:25.480
They have protect.

00:33:25.480 --> 00:33:27.860
&gt;&gt; Carrie N. Lyons:
Hard rock, right?

00:33:27.860 --> 00:33:31.050
&gt;&gt; Armstrong Wiggins: We have
Seminoles, I think that was one

00:33:31.050 --> 00:33:34.310
of my interesting experience.

00:33:34.310 --> 00:33:38.420
Because they don't
believe in compromising.

00:33:38.420 --> 00:33:41.180
They believe that they
need to be left alone.

00:33:41.180 --> 00:33:44.520
They want to have their
own traditional ceremonies.

00:33:44.520 --> 00:33:49.280
And they lost land and so
they used to borrow land

00:33:49.280 --> 00:33:51.750
from citrus growers in Florida,

00:33:51.750 --> 00:33:55.740
to do their green
dance ceremonies.

00:33:55.740 --> 00:34:01.560
And so they look to us for help,
how to get land that they lost

00:34:01.560 --> 00:34:04.980
to have their traditional
and then their homes,

00:34:04.980 --> 00:34:09.530
to build their homes the way
they want, tipis, basically.

00:34:09.530 --> 00:34:12.320
And so we represented them.

00:34:12.320 --> 00:34:16.170
And I think that was very
difficult from my experience,

00:34:16.170 --> 00:34:17.970
because they won't compromise.

00:34:17.970 --> 00:34:21.720
In other words, it's
hard to negotiate

00:34:21.720 --> 00:34:24.260
between non-Indian verses them.

00:34:24.260 --> 00:34:30.400
But we were lucky to go outside
of Florida to look for help.

00:34:30.400 --> 00:34:33.500
I don't know if you heard
about land foundation?

00:34:33.500 --> 00:34:37.780
It's based in Santa
Fe, New Mexico.

00:34:37.780 --> 00:34:39.800
It's a very rich family.

00:34:39.800 --> 00:34:47.630
Patrick Lannan, one day, knocked
at my door here in DC and said,

00:34:47.630 --> 00:34:51.310
in a blue jean, you know,
dressed like somebody

00:34:51.310 --> 00:34:52.660
that don't have money.

00:34:52.660 --> 00:34:56.720
And he said, I am Patrick Lannan
and I want to talk to you guys

00:34:56.720 --> 00:34:59.070
about how we can help.

00:34:59.070 --> 00:35:00.470
&gt;&gt; Carrie N. Lyons:
Help the Seminoles.

00:35:00.470 --> 00:35:01.770
&gt;&gt; Armstrong Wiggins:
Not only the Seminoles,

00:35:01.770 --> 00:35:03.070
Indian Law Resource Center.

00:35:03.070 --> 00:35:04.370
&gt;&gt; Carrie N. Lyons: Oh.

00:35:04.370 --> 00:35:05.670
&gt;&gt; Armstrong Wiggins: We
are interested in education.

00:35:05.670 --> 00:35:09.350
We want to help tribal
government, technical schools.

00:35:09.350 --> 00:35:11.780
We want to get them money.

00:35:11.780 --> 00:35:13.080
And so I'm here.

00:35:13.080 --> 00:35:16.070
I heard about you guys
and we want to talk.

00:35:16.070 --> 00:35:17.850
And that's how we started.

00:35:17.850 --> 00:35:22.330
And Patrick Lannan paid for
this huge land in Florida

00:35:22.330 --> 00:35:25.360
for the Seminoles, $1.5 million.

00:35:25.360 --> 00:35:26.660
&gt;&gt; Carrie N. Lyons: Wow.

00:35:26.660 --> 00:35:28.330
&gt;&gt; Armstrong Wiggins: From the
citrus growers that they used

00:35:28.330 --> 00:35:30.330
to do their ceremonies.

00:35:30.330 --> 00:35:32.700
And so now they have a land

00:35:32.700 --> 00:35:35.750
that is not only the
Seminole have a land

00:35:35.750 --> 00:35:37.230
to do their traditional work,

00:35:37.230 --> 00:35:40.290
but this land will be
protected environmentally.

00:35:40.290 --> 00:35:45.260
This land, they have bald
eagles, they have alligators,

00:35:45.260 --> 00:35:49.820
and there's not in that
destructive way of development.

00:35:49.820 --> 00:35:52.610
And then the other fight
we had with the state

00:35:52.610 --> 00:35:54.540
of Florida was the Tipis.

00:35:54.540 --> 00:35:56.610
Because they wanted to
build their own homes.

00:35:56.610 --> 00:36:00.480
And because of rules
of building codes,

00:36:00.480 --> 00:36:02.630
the Florida government said, no.

00:36:02.630 --> 00:36:06.940
so we tried to get, you know,
all the newspaper on our side

00:36:06.940 --> 00:36:09.730
to make, you know, kind
of challenge the state.

00:36:09.730 --> 00:36:11.850
And state finally give in

00:36:11.850 --> 00:36:15.240
and let them build
their own typical homes

00:36:15.240 --> 00:36:18.150
to have their own
traditional ceremonies.

00:36:18.150 --> 00:36:19.450
&gt;&gt; Carrie N. Lyons: Wow.

00:36:19.450 --> 00:36:20.750
&gt;&gt; Armstrong Wiggins: And
so that's a great story.

00:36:20.750 --> 00:36:22.800
&gt;&gt; Carrie N. Lyons: Now,
that's a success story, yeah.

00:36:22.800 --> 00:36:24.270
&gt;&gt; Armstrong Wiggins: And the
other day I was riding the--

00:36:24.270 --> 00:36:28.300
I ride the metro from
Washington, from Virginia to DC.

00:36:28.300 --> 00:36:31.320
And there were some native
kids, high school kids.

00:36:31.320 --> 00:36:33.440
And they were laughing
and joking.

00:36:33.440 --> 00:36:37.010
And they come and sit by
me and start talking to me.

00:36:37.010 --> 00:36:38.660
And I said, where you from?

00:36:38.660 --> 00:36:42.200
And he said, I'm a
Seminole from Florida.

00:36:42.200 --> 00:36:43.510
We're visiting Washington.

00:36:43.510 --> 00:36:44.810
&gt;&gt; Carrie N. Lyons: Wow.

00:36:44.810 --> 00:36:46.240
&gt;&gt; Armstrong Wiggins: I said,
do you know Uncle Billy?

00:36:46.240 --> 00:36:51.460
That's my uncle!

00:36:51.460 --> 00:36:52.760
&gt;&gt; Carrie N. Lyons: Wow.

00:36:52.760 --> 00:36:55.510
&gt;&gt; Armstrong Wiggins:
How do you know my uncle?

00:36:55.510 --> 00:36:56.870
Because I work with him.

00:36:56.870 --> 00:36:58.590
&gt;&gt; Carrie N. Lyons: Serendipity.

00:36:58.590 --> 00:37:00.250
&gt;&gt; Armstrong Wiggins:
They were excited.

00:37:00.250 --> 00:37:03.770
A week later the uncle
called me and said--

00:37:03.770 --> 00:37:05.880
&gt;&gt; Carrie N. Lyons:
Nice, very nice.

00:37:05.880 --> 00:37:09.320
Have there been any cases or
issues that you wanted to take

00:37:09.320 --> 00:37:11.930
that you've been unable
to take at the Center.

00:37:11.930 --> 00:37:13.290
&gt;&gt; Armstrong Wiggins:
Oh, there's so many.

00:37:13.290 --> 00:37:19.160
If we have, like some-- if we
get money from the government,

00:37:19.160 --> 00:37:22.390
the European government
offered lots of money,

00:37:22.390 --> 00:37:23.780
but we don't accept it.

00:37:23.780 --> 00:37:27.890
Because sometimes there
are conditions of why.

00:37:27.890 --> 00:37:34.330
There's so many cases, tenure
land title is so important

00:37:34.330 --> 00:37:37.460
to us, legal rights
to their land.

00:37:37.460 --> 00:37:43.140
And if you watch the world
changing toward our issues,

00:37:43.140 --> 00:37:47.350
European begin to support
Indian thinking about how

00:37:47.350 --> 00:37:52.790
to manage land, how to
manage natural resources,

00:37:52.790 --> 00:37:54.750
and climate issues.

00:37:54.750 --> 00:38:00.320
And so land titling
is very important

00:38:00.320 --> 00:38:03.600
so that indigenous people
can manage their land.

00:38:03.600 --> 00:38:05.810
Protected area, how
we protect our way

00:38:05.810 --> 00:38:08.870
from World Wildlife Fund,
Conservation International

00:38:08.870 --> 00:38:14.170
and others, that only follow
the money trail, especially USA.

00:38:14.170 --> 00:38:18.340
But when that money
finished, they move back

00:38:18.340 --> 00:38:21.650
to [inaudible] City, or
they move back to Roselyn,

00:38:21.650 --> 00:38:23.340
because they don't have
money to stay there.

00:38:23.340 --> 00:38:26.550
So then the bad guys move in
and destroy the environment.

00:38:26.550 --> 00:38:29.170
And they don't respect
indigenous people land rights.

00:38:29.170 --> 00:38:31.240
They only work with
the central government.

00:38:31.240 --> 00:38:33.080
And so that's the problem.

00:38:33.080 --> 00:38:35.810
If indigenous people
managed those areas,

00:38:35.810 --> 00:38:38.320
those land like Bosawas
Nicaragua,

00:38:38.320 --> 00:38:41.230
and many other people
in Brazil, you know.

00:38:41.230 --> 00:38:43.470
Only the bone that fell

00:38:43.470 --> 00:38:46.470
from these environmental
organization, they get money

00:38:46.470 --> 00:38:49.960
from USAID goes to
the indigenous people.

00:38:49.960 --> 00:38:52.500
But then when they move
out, indigenous people have

00:38:52.500 --> 00:38:55.050
to face the poacher, the people

00:38:55.050 --> 00:38:58.040
that cut their land
and their territory.

00:38:58.040 --> 00:39:01.180
We would like to work
for them in Brazil.

00:39:01.180 --> 00:39:06.800
We would like to work with
them with the Brazilian banks.

00:39:06.800 --> 00:39:11.940
That is very, very bad against
Indian land rights issues,

00:39:11.940 --> 00:39:14.660
take away Indian lands
by building the highways

00:39:14.660 --> 00:39:18.700
and the dams and
stuff like that.

00:39:18.700 --> 00:39:20.000
Do you know that the
[Foreign Language],

00:39:20.000 --> 00:39:23.150
which is the Brazil
bank, has more money

00:39:23.150 --> 00:39:25.350
than World Bank right now?

00:39:25.350 --> 00:39:27.900
And so they give very
destructive development

00:39:27.900 --> 00:39:31.850
that is not good for
indigenous people.

00:39:31.850 --> 00:39:36.000
So we try to work with
educate these banks

00:39:36.000 --> 00:39:38.260
and develop legal mechanism

00:39:38.260 --> 00:39:40.640
to restrict indigenous
people land rights.

00:39:40.640 --> 00:39:43.750
But we don't have all
that money to do that.

00:39:43.750 --> 00:39:46.530
European are now beginning
to give some money.

00:39:46.530 --> 00:39:49.200
They just created an
institute in Stockholm

00:39:49.200 --> 00:39:51.880
about Indian land tenure issues.

00:39:51.880 --> 00:39:53.180
&gt;&gt; Carrie N. Lyons: Oh, wow.

00:39:53.180 --> 00:39:54.480
&gt;&gt; Armstrong Wiggins: But
I don't know if it will go

00:39:54.480 --> 00:39:55.780
to the indigenous people.

00:39:55.780 --> 00:39:57.080
And that's the thing.

00:39:57.080 --> 00:39:58.380
There are a lot of
discrimination about money given

00:39:58.380 --> 00:40:00.210
to indigenous people also.

00:40:00.210 --> 00:40:04.980
And because, you
know, intermediaries.

00:40:04.980 --> 00:40:06.280
&gt;&gt; Carrie N. Lyons:
Right, right.

00:40:06.280 --> 00:40:09.540
Leo, is there any case you
wish you could have taken?

00:40:09.540 --> 00:40:10.840
&gt;&gt; Leonardo A. Crippa:
Most of the--

00:40:10.840 --> 00:40:12.570
I mean, reason why
we don't take a lot

00:40:12.570 --> 00:40:15.040
of cases is money, basically.

00:40:15.040 --> 00:40:18.160
We can't represent all the
clients that we would like to.

00:40:18.160 --> 00:40:21.670
So we are very selective
of the cases that we take,

00:40:21.670 --> 00:40:24.510
especially looking
into the issues.

00:40:24.510 --> 00:40:27.430
If we take a case,
we will, basically,

00:40:27.430 --> 00:40:32.240
gain reform in the
politics of that country.

00:40:32.240 --> 00:40:34.310
That's the main reason.

00:40:34.310 --> 00:40:38.380
However, there are situations
where we start looking

00:40:38.380 --> 00:40:41.130
to the case, documenting
the facts,

00:40:41.130 --> 00:40:45.150
starting to interview local
authorities about the issues

00:40:45.150 --> 00:40:48.510
that the indigenous
communities are concerned.

00:40:48.510 --> 00:40:51.620
In the end, when we are about
to take the legal action,

00:40:51.620 --> 00:40:53.090
and we have secured
some resources,

00:40:53.090 --> 00:40:55.140
the issue is resolved.

00:40:55.140 --> 00:40:56.510
So no case, right?

00:40:56.510 --> 00:40:59.190
I can mention a few examples.

00:40:59.190 --> 00:41:01.100
One is the [inaudible]
community.

00:41:01.100 --> 00:41:06.810
It's a [inaudible] community
in the Peruvian Amazon,

00:41:06.810 --> 00:41:10.120
close to the border with Brazil.

00:41:10.120 --> 00:41:16.360
There was an interoceanic
highway was going to be built

00:41:16.360 --> 00:41:20.010
with funds coming from both
the Brazil Development Bank

00:41:20.010 --> 00:41:22.630
and the Inter-American
Development Bank that will,

00:41:22.630 --> 00:41:25.150
basically, connect
Brazil [inaudible]

00:41:25.150 --> 00:41:30.180
on the Brazil side
with Pucullpa Peru.

00:41:30.180 --> 00:41:33.440
And will, basically,
divide up the land

00:41:33.440 --> 00:41:37.800
where this community
was located.

00:41:37.800 --> 00:41:42.730
And so we started to inquire
where the funds were coming,

00:41:42.730 --> 00:41:47.810
the permits that these companies
had to build that road.

00:41:47.810 --> 00:41:50.590
In the middle of that,
the [inaudible] the head

00:41:50.590 --> 00:41:55.120
of this community started
to talk to civil society,

00:41:55.120 --> 00:41:58.570
locally in Pucullpa,
and there nationally

00:41:58.570 --> 00:42:01.420
in Lima, the capital of Peru.

00:42:01.420 --> 00:42:03.870
So we started to make
some noise about it.

00:42:03.870 --> 00:42:06.220
And in the middle of that,

00:42:06.220 --> 00:42:08.000
the transportation
authorities started

00:42:08.000 --> 00:42:10.510
to cancel all the permits.

00:42:10.510 --> 00:42:13.090
They basically redesigned
the project, and as a result,

00:42:13.090 --> 00:42:15.110
they weren't going to
divide up that community.

00:42:15.110 --> 00:42:16.410
And so we had no case to take.

00:42:16.410 --> 00:42:17.710
&gt;&gt; Carrie N. Lyons: OK.

00:42:17.710 --> 00:42:19.660
&gt;&gt; Leonardo A. Crippa: And
there were some cases like that.

00:42:19.660 --> 00:42:21.820
But mainly it is a
lack of resources.

00:42:21.820 --> 00:42:27.140
We are very selective about the
cases, because we actually want

00:42:27.140 --> 00:42:29.430
to have a huge impact
on the country.

00:42:29.430 --> 00:42:33.410
And we want one case to
benefit not only our client,

00:42:33.410 --> 00:42:37.010
