to get their lands, conservation
organizations trying

00:56:43.950 --> 00:56:46.810
to manage their natural
resources.

00:56:46.810 --> 00:56:49.760
And sometimes we get
supports, sometimes not.

00:56:49.760 --> 00:56:53.690
But we find ways to work through
the legal system of the country

00:56:53.690 --> 00:56:56.440
or this international
organization.

00:56:56.440 --> 00:57:00.210
So that we can either get
an international instrument,

00:57:00.210 --> 00:57:03.670
like the declarations on the
rights of indigenous peoples,

00:57:03.670 --> 00:57:07.420
or ban policies on indigenous
peoples in an actual case

00:57:07.420 --> 00:57:10.610
to change the way indigenous
peoples are treated sometimes.

00:57:10.610 --> 00:57:13.050
I hope that clarifies
this a bit.

00:57:13.050 --> 00:57:16.000
&gt;&gt; Armstrong Wiggins: I think
also, to try to understand,

00:57:16.000 --> 00:57:20.600
when you say, a vicious
circle, what I want you

00:57:20.600 --> 00:57:23.200
to understand that, we,
from our perspective,

00:57:23.200 --> 00:57:26.540
we do respect collective
and individual rights.

00:57:26.540 --> 00:57:28.050
We respect that.

00:57:28.050 --> 00:57:35.270
I was jailed in my territory,
my people defended me.

00:57:35.270 --> 00:57:36.990
That's why I'm alive.

00:57:36.990 --> 00:57:40.300
I was arrested in Managua,
Nicaragua, in the capital

00:57:40.300 --> 00:57:43.970
from my office, close to
the [inaudible] office.

00:57:43.970 --> 00:57:48.470
I was defended through
my individual rights,

00:57:48.470 --> 00:57:51.370
not collective rights,
through my villages, OK?

00:57:51.370 --> 00:57:55.490
So, sometimes it benefits us
and we respect one aspect of it.

00:57:55.490 --> 00:57:57.640
But let me just tell you one
example what just happened

00:57:57.640 --> 00:57:59.300
to us not too long ago.

00:57:59.300 --> 00:58:03.090
We, trying to get
money from law offices,

00:58:03.090 --> 00:58:05.440
but there're sometimes
conflict of interest.

00:58:05.440 --> 00:58:08.010
We had been trying to get
money from corporation,

00:58:08.010 --> 00:58:09.310
but sometimes there
might be conflict

00:58:09.310 --> 00:58:12.050
of interest, from corporation.

00:58:12.050 --> 00:58:13.350
We got some money

00:58:13.350 --> 00:58:15.220
from Mitsubishi Foundation
in New York.

00:58:15.220 --> 00:58:18.550
It's this Japanese car
maker's foundation.

00:58:18.550 --> 00:58:23.760
We decided, maybe, we can get
that to work with the red issue

00:58:23.760 --> 00:58:25.830
that you heard about,
talk about.

00:58:25.830 --> 00:58:27.130
This is environmental issue.

00:58:27.130 --> 00:58:30.100
Environmental is know what
is red, a red program.

00:58:30.100 --> 00:58:33.120
The European come up with a
list environmental thinking.

00:58:33.120 --> 00:58:37.200
The first one is gift,
then now red, OK?

00:58:37.200 --> 00:58:40.620
Which mean the, what they were,
if you have a lot of trees,

00:58:40.620 --> 00:58:44.000
you can get money from your
trees that is in your yard or is

00:58:44.000 --> 00:58:45.300
in your community, OK?

00:58:45.300 --> 00:58:46.710
That's red program.

00:58:46.710 --> 00:58:48.640
So Mitsubishi was
interested in that.

00:58:48.640 --> 00:58:52.640
But when we met with that, we
didn't know when we decided

00:58:52.640 --> 00:58:56.620
to represent indigenous people
in Mexico about the wind issues

00:58:56.620 --> 00:58:58.240
that I just talk about.

00:58:58.240 --> 00:59:01.210
One of the biggest money
was coming from Mitsubishi

00:59:01.210 --> 00:59:03.680
and Inter-American
Development Bank.

00:59:03.680 --> 00:59:09.590
And so Mitsubishi said, you
stop representing the Indians

00:59:09.590 --> 00:59:11.500
or we will not give
you the money.

00:59:11.500 --> 00:59:16.840
And we said, we will not stop
it, you can stop the money.

00:59:16.840 --> 00:59:18.440
And that's what we did, OK?

00:59:18.440 --> 00:59:19.740
Something that--

00:59:19.740 --> 00:59:21.040
&gt;&gt; Carrie N. Lyons:
It's a balance, yeah.

00:59:21.040 --> 00:59:22.340
&gt;&gt; Armstrong Wiggins:
It's a balance.

00:59:22.340 --> 00:59:23.640
So I just wanted to
clarify that too.

00:59:23.640 --> 00:59:24.940
&gt;&gt; Carrie N. Lyons: So
I think we have time

00:59:24.940 --> 00:59:27.160
for one last question.

00:59:27.160 --> 00:59:30.450
&gt;&gt; Audience: You have in
Guatemala, which has almost half

00:59:30.450 --> 00:59:32.230
of its population indigenous.

00:59:32.230 --> 00:59:34.780
And they have been
considering a law

00:59:35.830 --> 00:59:40.170
that would recognize
indigenous law to some degree.

00:59:41.220 --> 00:59:43.660
But it stalled, in part,
because of objections

00:59:43.660 --> 00:59:47.440
from business communities
that might be able

00:59:47.440 --> 00:59:50.430
to exploit natural
resources, indigenous lands,

00:59:50.430 --> 00:59:51.740
and for other reasons.

00:59:51.740 --> 00:59:58.190
So I wanted to know if you could
discuss how can indigenous law,

00:59:58.190 --> 01:00:03.380
with its main emphasis
on collective property,

01:00:03.380 --> 01:00:05.290
collective right, coexist
with, like, the national laws

01:00:05.290 --> 01:00:08.090
of a country like Guatemala that
emphasizes individual rights?

01:00:08.090 --> 01:00:13.260
How can you have those
two function and coexist?

01:00:14.350 --> 01:00:15.670
&gt;&gt; Leonardo A. Crippa: There
are some precedents still

01:00:15.670 --> 01:00:17.040
in Guatemala.

01:00:17.040 --> 01:00:23.580
I remember a decision issued
by the Conditional Court

01:00:23.580 --> 01:00:28.920
where it was a Supreme Court
case against [inaudible],

01:00:28.920 --> 01:00:31.080
a member of my community,

01:00:31.080 --> 01:00:37.700
after the Maya approached his
community and applies a sanction

01:00:37.700 --> 01:00:44.880
against him because
of behavior that was

01:00:44.880 --> 01:00:48.150
against the community's
traditions.

01:00:48.150 --> 01:00:50.610
But, anyway, his case ended

01:00:50.610 --> 01:00:55.440
up in the Guatemala
criminal system.

01:00:55.440 --> 01:01:00.990
So that case brought to
the conventional courts,

01:01:00.990 --> 01:01:05.500
the conditional court
basically said indigenous people

01:01:05.500 --> 01:01:09.600
of Guatemala have a legal system

01:01:09.600 --> 01:01:13.370
in which they can
resort authorities.

01:01:13.370 --> 01:01:18.440
And a policy where criminal
issues have been addressed

01:01:18.440 --> 01:01:23.550
by the own community, the
state courts cannot reduce

01:01:23.550 --> 01:01:27.630
to persecute those that
haven't already been sanctioned

01:01:27.630 --> 01:01:28.930
by traditional groups.

01:01:28.930 --> 01:01:31.660
So that court, the
traditional court,

01:01:31.660 --> 01:01:33.800
applied what is non-criminal
law.

01:01:33.800 --> 01:01:40.340
They [inaudible], which
means, no one tell me subject

01:01:40.340 --> 01:01:42.750
to criminal charges once.

01:01:42.750 --> 01:01:47.740
But that's just one
example, and one precedent.

01:01:47.740 --> 01:01:53.180
And I remember this because a
lawmaker [inaudible] was one

01:01:53.180 --> 01:01:57.470
of the authorities [inaudible]
members of my community.

01:02:01.110 --> 01:02:05.750
And the controversy around
collective land rights

01:02:05.750 --> 01:02:11.070
and the country's
legal system oriented

01:02:11.070 --> 01:02:15.410
to protect private property,

01:02:15.410 --> 01:02:19.280
that's not such a
big controversy

01:02:19.280 --> 01:02:27.080
because there are already
laws in Guatemala that tend

01:02:27.080 --> 01:02:31.470
to protect collective lands.

01:02:31.470 --> 01:02:36.250
Like, for example, the
law that the created the--

01:02:36.250 --> 01:02:38.040
it is called the
[foreign language].

01:02:38.040 --> 01:02:42.390
That basically will execute and
enforce all of the agrarian laws

01:02:42.390 --> 01:02:45.550
that were passed by
Congress in Guatemala.

01:02:45.550 --> 01:02:50.480
And that law, it tries to
provide some protection

01:02:50.480 --> 01:02:52.820
for peasant communities.

01:02:52.820 --> 01:02:58.070
In that way, it was
good objective.

01:02:58.070 --> 01:03:00.110
But it wasn't, at the same time,

01:03:00.110 --> 01:03:03.670
not as good because indigenous
peoples were included there

01:03:03.670 --> 01:03:06.190
as peasant communities,
until we solved all

01:03:06.190 --> 01:03:08.230
of the agrarian policies
are applied

01:03:08.230 --> 01:03:11.960
to indigenous communities

01:03:11.960 --> 01:03:14.400
as though they were
peasant communities,

01:03:14.400 --> 01:03:16.440
without consider their legal
nature as indigenous people.

01:03:16.440 --> 01:03:21.400
We call this right are
recognized by international law

01:03:21.400 --> 01:03:23.680
in the paper and so forth.

01:03:23.680 --> 01:03:26.900
So there are some precedents
in both court positions

01:03:26.900 --> 01:03:30.820
and in actual legislation
that tend

01:03:30.820 --> 01:03:33.700
to protect collective
[inaudible] lands.

01:03:33.700 --> 01:03:37.890
But, unfortunately, Guatemala,
there is no actual legislation

01:03:37.890 --> 01:03:42.470
that recognizes indigenous
people's communities legal

01:03:42.470 --> 01:03:46.650
personality, nor their
collective ownership

01:03:46.650 --> 01:03:48.410
over the lands that
they possess.

01:03:48.410 --> 01:03:51.140
And that is why we started them,

01:03:51.140 --> 01:03:54.990
whenever there is a conservation
project on Indian lands,

01:03:54.990 --> 01:03:59.250
or a constructive energy
project on native lands.

01:03:59.250 --> 01:04:03.420
But, I would say, the best way
to work towards a reconciliation

01:04:03.420 --> 01:04:07.350
of these different laws
or legal approaches is

01:04:07.350 --> 01:04:11.570
by making indigenous
peoples sit at the table

01:04:11.570 --> 01:04:15.460
and have an ad hoc
conversation with them.

01:04:15.460 --> 01:04:19.030
So that when we stand here,
them, and they can participate

01:04:19.030 --> 01:04:21.230
in the development
of [inaudible].

01:04:21.230 --> 01:04:26.520
And that is something that
already happened in Peru.

01:04:26.520 --> 01:04:28.900
The consultation
that was [inaudible].

01:04:32.200 --> 01:04:34.250
&gt;&gt; Armstrong Wiggins: I think
it's a very good question,

01:04:34.250 --> 01:04:37.400
and sometimes have
me sleepless nights.

01:04:37.400 --> 01:04:44.350
And I remember when Kofi Annan
was the Secretary-General

01:04:44.350 --> 01:04:45.650
of the UN.

01:04:45.650 --> 01:04:49.420
He went to Bolivia for the first
time, and then he came back.

01:04:49.420 --> 01:04:52.230
And he called me up and
said, can we have lunch?

01:04:52.230 --> 01:04:55.640
So I had lunch with him
right at 8th Street.

01:04:55.640 --> 01:04:57.920
Now we get famous.

01:04:57.920 --> 01:05:03.560
And one of Kofi Annan
question to me was Armstrong.

01:05:03.560 --> 01:05:08.480
I know that Bolivian
are indigenous majority,

01:05:08.480 --> 01:05:09.880
just like Guatemala.

01:05:09.880 --> 01:05:13.390
But he didn't go to Guatemala,
he was coming from Bolivia.

01:05:13.390 --> 01:05:18.230
And he said, but how
can we find a leader

01:05:18.230 --> 01:05:21.800
that can bring everybody
together instead

01:05:21.800 --> 01:05:27.920
of taking what happened
to them to take to go

01:05:27.920 --> 01:05:31.250
against the minority,
non-indigenous people.

01:05:31.250 --> 01:05:35.220
How we find, in Bolivia,
something what happened

01:05:35.220 --> 01:05:39.710
in South Africa, you know,
by South African leader?

01:05:39.710 --> 01:05:42.570
And so it's a tough question.

01:05:42.570 --> 01:05:44.780
I said, I don't have the answer.

01:05:44.780 --> 01:05:50.160
We just-- education is key
to do, to do that, you know,

01:05:50.160 --> 01:05:52.180
like what happened
in South Africa.

01:05:52.180 --> 01:05:54.910
Even though he was in jail
that long, became president

01:05:54.910 --> 01:05:58.570
and he worked with everybody
and pulled everybody together.

01:05:58.570 --> 01:06:01.030
Guatemala situation
is the same thing.

01:06:01.030 --> 01:06:04.760
And yet, if you think
about in China,

01:06:04.760 --> 01:06:06.780
it's a communist country, right?

01:06:06.780 --> 01:06:10.940
China? China economy is
taking all of our bills here

01:06:10.940 --> 01:06:13.150
in the United States
because China keep pulling

01:06:13.150 --> 01:06:14.450
out of our debt, right?

01:06:14.450 --> 01:06:21.370
And so, what's going on in
China is now they're bringing

01:06:21.370 --> 01:06:25.590
to their politburo,
all the rich people.

01:06:25.590 --> 01:06:27.630
But they can't question
the collectivity,

01:06:27.630 --> 01:06:30.350
the corporative system
of Chinese system

01:06:30.350 --> 01:06:32.740
of government, you know.

01:06:32.740 --> 01:06:35.510
So one of the thing that
we're thinking, hoping,

01:06:35.510 --> 01:06:41.870
is that we get education to
all indigenous communities.

01:06:41.870 --> 01:06:45.720
That they can become
voting power.

01:06:45.720 --> 01:06:47.560
And it's not hard.

01:06:47.560 --> 01:06:52.790
In Guatemala, probably
60% in majority.

01:06:52.790 --> 01:06:58.340
Can you imagine if they vote in
what your founding fathers said,

01:06:58.340 --> 01:07:00.610
our founding fathers said here?

01:07:00.610 --> 01:07:04.810
That educated people
can vote the right way

01:07:04.810 --> 01:07:07.370
that who they believe
can be a good leader.

01:07:07.370 --> 01:07:10.600
That's not what happened
in Guatemala, OK?

01:07:10.600 --> 01:07:15.010
So if they can vote their
own president, Mayan leader

01:07:15.010 --> 01:07:18.300
like [inaudible] will
become the president.

01:07:18.300 --> 01:07:20.550
But we're not there yet.

01:07:20.550 --> 01:07:24.410
Even Inter-American Court of
Human Rights, in San Jose,

01:07:24.410 --> 01:07:31.220
Costa Rica, which is the OAS
Inter-American System ruled

01:07:31.220 --> 01:07:33.040
with the case of
Yatama vs. Nicaragua.

01:07:33.040 --> 01:07:35.130
And they ruled in favor

01:07:35.130 --> 01:07:37.700
of indigenous people
have the rights

01:07:37.700 --> 01:07:41.610
to have election
according to their history,

01:07:41.610 --> 01:07:44.560
according to their
culture, not enforced

01:07:44.560 --> 01:07:48.400
by the capital city
political parties.

01:07:48.400 --> 01:07:50.380
If that happened in Guatemala,

01:07:50.380 --> 01:07:54.460
and I'm Indian person can be
offered this in Guatemala.

01:07:54.460 --> 01:07:56.250
But we're not there yet.

01:07:56.250 --> 01:07:59.880
And so if Indian person can
be in Guatemala, president,

01:07:59.880 --> 01:08:02.610
and negotiate with the
business community,

01:08:02.610 --> 01:08:06.050
I'm sure they can meet
in the middle ground

01:08:06.050 --> 01:08:10.500
to have a better life for
indigenous [inaudible].

01:08:10.500 --> 01:08:11.800
They can negotiate that.

01:08:11.800 --> 01:08:13.440
But we're not there yet.

01:08:13.440 --> 01:08:15.610
But it will happen,
I'm telling you.

01:08:15.610 --> 01:08:18.160
Not in my lifetime,
but in the future,

01:08:18.160 --> 01:08:22.900
that probably will happen,
because they're the majority.

